%N A389888 Discriminants of real quadratic fields in which every additively indecomposable element is a unit.
%C A389888 For any totally real field K, an additively indecomposable element of K is a totally positive element in the maximal order of K which cannot be written as the sum of two totally positive integral elements of K.  Here, an element x of K is totally positive if all conjugates of x are positive real numbers. Any totally positive unit is additively indecomposable, although the converse need not hold.
%H A389888 Robin Visser, <a href="/A389888/b389888.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..2000</a>
%H A389888 Valentin Blomer and Vítězslav Kala, <a href="https://doi.org/10.25537/dm.2018v23.15-34">On the rank of universal quadratic forms over real quadratic fields</a>, Doc. Math. 23 (2018), 15-34.
%H A389888 Andreas Dress and Rudolf Scharlau, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-314X(82)90064-6">Indecomposable totally positive numbers in real quadratic orders</a>, J. Number Theory 14 (1982), no. 3, 292-306.
%H A389888 Oskar Perron, <a href="https://archive.org/details/dielehrevondenk00perrgoog/page/55/mode/2up">Die Lehre von den Kettenbrüchen</a>, Teubner, Leipzig, 1913. See Section 16, pages 55-63.
%H A389888 Magdaléna Tinková and Pavlo Yatsyna, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.05991">Additively indecomposable quadratic forms over totally real number fields</a>, arXiv:2502.05991 [math.NT], 2025.
%F A389888 If k is a discriminant of a real quadratic field, then k is an element of this sequence if and only if A387203(A013928(D)+1) = 1, where D = k if k = 1 (mod 4), otherwise D = k/4.
%e A389888 a(1) = 5, as Q(sqrt(5)) has discriminant 5 and all additively indecomposable elements of Q(sqrt(5)) are units.
%e A389888 a(2) = 12, as Q(sqrt(3)) has discriminant 12 and all additively indecomposable elements of Q(sqrt(3)) are units (e.g. see Tinková-Yatsyna, Section 5.5.2).
%e A389888 a(3) = 21, as Q(sqrt(21)) has discriminant 21 and all additively indecomposable elements of Q(sqrt(21)) are units (e.g. see Tinková-Yatsyna, Section 5.5.5).
%o A389888 (SageMath)
%o A389888 def is_A389888(k):
%o A389888     if ZZ(k).is_square(): return False
%o A389888     K.<a> = QuadraticField(k)
%o A389888     if K.disc() != k: return False
%o A389888     cf = continued_fraction((1+a)/2 if k%4==1 else a/2)
%o A389888     cp, s = cf.period(), cf.period_length()
%o A389888     if (s%2)==0: ans = sum([cp[i] for i in range(0, s-1, 2)])
%o A389888     elif (k%4)==0: ans = 2*cf[0]+sum([cp[i] for i in range(s-1)])
%o A389888     else: ans = 2*cf[0]+sum([cp[i] for i in range(s-1)])-1
%o A389888     return ans==1
%o A389888 print([k for k in range(1, 1000) if is_A389888(k)])
